</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[361,767,526,582]" box="[478,649,558,582]" pageId="22" pageNumber="179">(®gures 38±45)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="182" pageId="22" pageNumber="179" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[86,1042,622,742]" lastBlockId="23.[86,1042,1513,1697]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="22" pageNumber="179">
The living ciliates of this and related genera are very variable in shape, number of nuclei, mode and degree of silver impregnation, cell size, and in the number of somatic kineties. These ciliates are well known as rapacious carnivores (see 
<bibRefCitation author="CORLISS, J. O." pageId="22" pageNumber="179" refId="ref11842" refString="CORLISS, J. O., 1979, T he Ciliated Protozoa: Characterization, Classi ® cation, and Guide to the L iterature, 2 nd edn (Oxford and New York: Pergamon Press)." type="book" year="1979">Corliss, 1979</bibRefCitation>
). Starved cells are normally elongate with the oral aperture at the top of the anterior end (®gures 38±45), and with no obvious caudal cilia. A large number of very similar nominal species (an example is shown in ®gure 45) have been described, with dierences between them as slight as the number of macronuclei. Taxonomic revision of the genera involved falls outside the scope of this paper.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5279494" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5279494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5279494/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="179" startId="22.[86,102,1596,1617]" targetBox="[161,966,830,1539]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph blockId="22.[86,1041,1595,1696]" pageId="22" pageNumber="179">
FIG. 38. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[190,398,1595,1617]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="22" pageNumber="179" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[190,398,1595,1617]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="179">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Morphological variants, and arrangement of the infraciliature. Note the disposition of the mitochondria (Mt) in longitudinal rows, and the variation in the number of macronuclei. C, clavate cilia; CV, contractile vacuole; E, extrusomes; K, circumoral kinety; Ma, macronucleus; mi, micronucleus; Mt, mitochondria.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280461" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5280461" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280461/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="180" startId="23.[86,102,1251,1272]" targetBox="[95,1032,139,1213]" targetPageId="23">
<paragraph blockId="23.[86,1043,1251,1459]" pageId="23" pageNumber="180">
FIGS 39±44. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[228,441,1251,1273]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="23" pageNumber="180" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[228,441,1251,1273]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="180">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; (39) cultured organisms in an oxygen gradient (the air bubble is at the top margin of the photograph). The organisms accumulate at some distance from oxygen-saturated water, i.e. at the oxic-anoxic boundary. Arrows to some conjugating individuals; (40, 44) two dierent cell shapes, each with two macronuclei. Arrows in (44) to the clavate cilia; (41±43) silver-impregnated specimens: (41, 43) silver-carbonate impregnation; (42) protargol. CV, contractile vacuole; E, extrusomes; FV, food vacuole; K, circumoral kinety; Ma, macronucleus; arrowheads in (43) at the somatic kineties that bear clavate cilia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="23.[86,1042,1513,1697]" lastBlockId="25.[86,1043,142,1696]" lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="182" pageId="23" pageNumber="180">
The amount of food ingested, and the stage of the life cycle, dictate the shape and size of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[218,344,1672,1696]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="23" pageNumber="180" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[218,344,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="180">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(®gure 38). It varies between 45 and 
<quantity box="[773,818,1672,1696]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="180" unit="m" value="60.0">
60 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[804,818,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="180">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m long, and 17 and 
<quantity box="[86,132,1449,1473]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" unit="m" value="25.0">
25 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[118,132,1449,1473]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m wide although very small cells were occasionally observed. The full morphological diversity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[285,412,1481,1505]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[285,412,1481,1505]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was assessed by preparing dierent cultures and using 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O. F. MuEller" baseAuthorityYear="1786" box="[86,297,1513,1536]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Uronematidae" genus="Uronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[86,297,1513,1536]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Uronema nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as food (®gure 39). The shape can be ellipsoidal (e.g. 
<quantity box="[916,961,1513,1537]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" unit="m" value="45.0">
45 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[947,961,1513,1537]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m long by 
<quantity box="[125,170,1545,1569]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" unit="m" value="23.0">
23 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[156,170,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m wide); elongate, tapering towards the posterior end (e.g. 
<quantity box="[874,920,1545,1569]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" unit="m" value="60.0">
60 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[906,920,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m long by 17.5 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[138,152,1577,1601]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">m</emphasis>
m wide); pear-shaped with broader anterior part of the cell, pointed at the anterior end and rounded at the posterior; or with a protruding cytostome (®gure 38). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[86,318,1641,1665]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[86,318,1641,1665]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the characteristics of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1838" box="[733,871,1641,1665]" class="Gymnostomatea" family="Enchelyidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="family">Enchelyidae</taxonomicName>
(as established by 
<bibRefCitation author="CORLISS, J. O." box="[127,280,1672,1696]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" refId="ref11842" refString="CORLISS, J. O., 1979, T he Ciliated Protozoa: Characterization, Classi ® cation, and Guide to the L iterature, 2 nd edn (Oxford and New York: Pergamon Press)." type="book" year="1979">Corliss, 1979</bibRefCitation>
): there is a ®eld of clavate sensory cilia, and the toxicysts are localized, typically in or near the oral area. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[588,821,142,166]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[588,821,142,166]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sparse somatic cilia and no obvious caudal cilia, although the cilia in that area do appear straighter than the rest (®gure 38). There is a single group of extrusomes (toxicysts?) gathered in a circle close to the oral aperture at the anterior part of the cell (®gures 41±43). This structure is detectable in silver-impregnated specimens, but hard to observe in living organisms (even in immobilized cells). In our experience, and assuming a good silver impregnation (either protargol or silver carbonate), this feature is observable only in one out of ®ve cells. There are other extrusomes scattered in the cytoplasm (®gure 41), which, again, were evident in only a few of the silver-impregnated cells examined.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280463" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5280463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280463/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" startId="24.[86,102,1230,1251]" targetBox="[272,856,144,1202]" targetPageId="24">
<paragraph blockId="24.[86,1043,1230,1384]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">
FIG. 45. Closely related genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[468,681,1230,1252]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[468,681,1230,1252]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[749,866,1230,1252]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[749,866,1230,1252]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="FOISSNER, W." box="[166,330,1256,1278]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" pagination="133" refId="ref12764" refString="FOISSNER, W., 1988, Gemeinsame Arten in der terricolen Ciliatenfauna (Protozoa: Ciliophora) von Australien und Afrika, Stap ® a, 17, 85 ± 133." type="journal article" year="1988">Foissner (1988)</bibRefCitation>
. (A) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Song and Wilbert" authorityYear="1989" box="[401,650,1256,1278]" class="Litostomatea" family="Trachelophyllidae" genus="Foissnerides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="heliophagus">
<emphasis box="[401,650,1256,1278]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Foissnerides heliophagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, after 
<bibRefCitation author="SONG, W. &amp; WILBERT, N." box="[729,987,1256,1278]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" pagination="223" refId="ref13478" refString="SONG, W. and WILBERT, N., 1989, Taxonomische Untersuchungen an Aufwuchsciliaten (Protozoa, Ciliophora) im Poppelsdorfer Weiher, Bonn, L auterbornia, 3, 1 ± 223." type="journal article" year="1989">Song and Wilbert, 1989</bibRefCitation>
. (B) 
<taxonomicName box="[166,405,1283,1305]" class="Prostomatea" family="Prorodontidae" genus="Pseudoprorodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="emmae">
<emphasis box="[166,405,1283,1305]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Pseudoprorodon emmae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, after 
<bibRefCitation author="SONG, W. &amp; WILBERT, N." box="[472,715,1283,1305]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" pagination="223" refId="ref13478" refString="SONG, W. and WILBERT, N., 1989, Taxonomische Untersuchungen an Aufwuchsciliaten (Protozoa, Ciliophora) im Poppelsdorfer Weiher, Bonn, L auterbornia, 3, 1 ± 223." type="journal article" year="1989">Song and Wilbert, 1989</bibRefCitation>
. (C) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[772,980,1283,1305]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[772,980,1283,1305]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="181">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, after 
<bibRefCitation author="FOISSNER, W." box="[166,310,1309,1331]" pageId="24" pageNumber="181" pagination="133" refId="ref12764" refString="FOISSNER, W., 1988, Gemeinsame Arten in der terricolen Ciliatenfauna (Protozoa: Ciliophora) von Australien und Afrika, Stap ® a, 17, 85 ± 133." type="journal article" year="1988">Foissner 1988</bibRefCitation>
. C, clavate cilia; CV, contractile vacuole; E, extrusomes; FV, food vacuole; Ma, macronucleus; mi, micronucleus. Note the continuous variation in the morphology of the organisms shown in (A)±(C).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="25.[86,1043,142,1696]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">
The somatic kineties are bipolar and dimorphic (®gures 38, 43). Half of them bear sensory bristles (
<bibRefCitation author="CORLISS, J. O." box="[332,479,499,523]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" refId="ref11842" refString="CORLISS, J. O., 1979, T he Ciliated Protozoa: Characterization, Classi ® cation, and Guide to the L iterature, 2 nd edn (Oxford and New York: Pergamon Press)." type="book" year="1979">Corliss, 1979</bibRefCitation>
), and therefore the infraciliature of these kineties diers from that of the other half (see below). In our population, the number of somatic kineties varied between 17 and 19, each kinety with few kinetids. Approximately half of the somatic kineties contain dikinetids with clavate cilia (about 1.9± 
<quantity box="[223,255,630,654]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="2.0">
2 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[241,255,630,654]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m long, ®gure 44) along their entire bipolar length, and these are easier to dierentiate in the area around the oral region. These clavate cilia constitute the sensory bristles (usually inaccurately termed`brosse’ in the literature), and the ciliates can bend them. The kinetids in these kineties are closer to each other at the anterior end of the cell (®gures 38, 43). The arrangement of the clavate cilia within a kinety varies between individuals and among kineties of the same specimen (®gure 38). It can be two clavate cilia together per kinetid, such as those around the oral aperture; one clavate cilium per kinetid; two clavate cilia plus a longer cilium (~ 
<quantity box="[122,182,890,914]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">
7±8 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,182,890,914]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m long) per kinetid; or one clavate cilium with one normal cilium per kinetid. The remaining somatic kineties bear single, scattered kinetosomes. The circular ®eld of extrusomes lies on this side of the cell (®gures 38, 42, 43).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[86,1043,142,1696]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">
The oral region is encircled by the circumoral kinety which has 17±19 paired kinetosomes lying side by side within each pair (®gures 38, 42, 43). The nematodesmata in the mouth are inconspicuous. In some living cells the mitochondria were observed arranged in bipolar rows, between the kineties (®gure 38). The contractile vacuole can appear round, elongate, or triangular, and situated at the cell posterior end. The number and shape of the macronuclei is variable too (®gure 38), the number varying from one to four macronuclei, although there is only one micronucleus. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[188,422,1216,1240]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[188,422,1216,1240]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Pleuroplites australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has previously been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[838,912,1216,1240]" name="Kenya" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[929,1033,1216,1240]" name="Australia" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Australia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[138,258,1248,1272]" name="Antarctica" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="FOISSNER, W." box="[278,442,1248,1272]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" pagination="235" refId="ref12889" refString="FOISSNER, W., 1998, An updated compilation of world soil ciliates (Protozoa, Ciliophora), with ecological notes, new records, and descriptions of new species, European Journal of Protistolology, 34, 195 ± 235." type="journal article" year="1998">Foissner, 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[86,1043,142,1696]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">
Living cells of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[306,435,1281,1305]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[306,435,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are indistinguishable from ciliates of the following genera: 
<taxonomicName authority=", Enchelys" authorityName="Enchelys" box="[181,408,1313,1337]" class="Gymnostomatea" family="Acropisthiidae" genus="Coriplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[181,289,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Coriplites</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[310,408,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Enchelys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Claparede &amp; Lachmann" authorityYear="1859" box="[428,567,1313,1337]" class="Litostomatea" family="Trachelophyllidae" genus="Enchelyodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[428,567,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Enchelyodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Song &amp; Wilbert" authorityYear="1989" box="[589,723,1313,1337]" class="Litostomatea" family="Trachelophyllidae" genus="Foissnerides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[589,723,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Foissnerides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1983" box="[742,848,1313,1337]" class="Gymnostomatea" family="Acropisthiidae" genus="Fuscheria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[742,848,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Fuscheria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1996" box="[869,1032,1313,1337]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplitoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,1032,1313,1337]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Pleuroplitoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from some of Kahl’s 
<taxonomicName box="[339,553,1346,1370]" class="Litostomatea" family="Spathidiidae" genus="Spathidium" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[339,462,1346,1370]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Spathidium</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, and from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kahl, 1926)" baseAuthorityName="Kahl" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[689,991,1346,1370]" class="Prostomatea" family="Prorodontidae" genus="Placus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="ovum">
<emphasis box="[689,830,1346,1370]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Placus ovum</emphasis>
(Kahl, 1926)
</taxonomicName>
. As stated above, a thorough revision of all these genera goes beyond the scope of this article. However, the peculiarity of the infraciliature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[733,861,1411,1435]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[733,861,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a ®eld of clavate cilia that involves more than half of the somatic kineties, and the existence of a localized group of toxicysts, resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[582,814,1476,1500]" class="Prostomatea" family="Prorodontidae" genus="Pseudoprorodon" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[582,759,1476,1500]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Pseudoprorodon</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
(see ®gure 45). The infraciliature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foissner" authorityYear="1988" box="[270,394,1509,1533]" class="Prostomatea" family="Pleuroplitidae" genus="Pleuroplites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Prostomatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[270,394,1509,1533]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also nearly identical to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Song and Wilbert, 1989" authorityName="Song and Wilbert" authorityYear="1989" class="Litostomatea" family="Trachelophyllidae" genus="Foissnerides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="heliophagus">
<emphasis box="[772,1042,1509,1533]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Foissnerides heliophagus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="SONG, W. &amp; WILBERT, N." box="[86,364,1541,1565]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" pagination="223" refId="ref13478" refString="SONG, W. and WILBERT, N., 1989, Taxonomische Untersuchungen an Aufwuchsciliaten (Protozoa, Ciliophora) im Poppelsdorfer Weiher, Bonn, L auterbornia, 3, 1 ± 223." type="journal article" year="1989">Song and Wilbert, 1989</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see ®gure 45, and 
<bibRefCitation author="SONG, W. &amp; WILBERT, N." box="[595,872,1541,1565]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" pagination="223" refId="ref13478" refString="SONG, W. and WILBERT, N., 1989, Taxonomische Untersuchungen an Aufwuchsciliaten (Protozoa, Ciliophora) im Poppelsdorfer Weiher, Bonn, L auterbornia, 3, 1 ± 223." type="journal article" year="1989">Song and Wilbert, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) with a single group of localized toxicysts near the oral aperture standing as the only dierence between the two. 
<bibRefCitation author="SONG, W. &amp; WILBERT, N." box="[291,578,1607,1631]" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" pagination="223" refId="ref13478" refString="SONG, W. and WILBERT, N., 1989, Taxonomische Untersuchungen an Aufwuchsciliaten (Protozoa, Ciliophora) im Poppelsdorfer Weiher, Bonn, L auterbornia, 3, 1 ± 223." type="journal article" year="1989">Song and Wilbert (1989)</bibRefCitation>
made no mention of this structure (but note that in our preparations it was observable in one out of ®ve silver-impregnated cells). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Song and Wilbert" authorityYear="1989" box="[161,432,1672,1696]" class="Litostomatea" family="Trachelophyllidae" genus="Foissnerides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Haptorida" pageId="25" pageNumber="182" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="heliophagus">
<emphasis box="[161,432,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Foissnerides heliophagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in 
<collectingCountry box="[599,705,1672,1696]" name="Germany" pageId="25" pageNumber="182">Germany</collectingCountry>
.
